  <title translate="true">Tip #32</title>
  <body>
    <para styleclass="Heading3"><text styleclass="Heading3" translate="true">Tip of the Day</text></para>
    <para styleclass="Normal"><table rowcount="1" colcount="2" style="cell-padding:0px; cell-spacing:0px; border-width:0px; cell-border-width:0px;">
      <tr style="vertical-align:top">
        <td style="width:58px;">
          <para styleclass="Normal"><image src="TipOfTheDayBulb.jpg" scale="100.00%" styleclass="Image Caption"></image></para>
        </td>
        <td style="width:328px;">
          <para styleclass="Normal"><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true">Adding a method to an existing class (</text><text styleclass="Class Name" translate="true">String</text><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true"> for example) to enhance it&apos;s behaviour is something that is quite acceptable in Smalltalk - unlike in some other languages. </text></para>
        </td>
      </tr>
    </table></para>
    <para styleclass="Normal"><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true">You must remember, though, that these enhancements will need to be re-implemented in any new image you upgrade to, so it is best to add them all to a &quot;</text><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true">My Enhancements&quot;</text><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true"> package that can easily be migrated. When added to a package, such methods are called &quot;loose methods&quot; because they are maintained by the package and not by the class to which they belong.</text><snippet src="Tip_Of_The_Day_Footer"/></para>
  </body>
